Think deeply about the security analysis problem of evaluating a website's complete frontend security posture from an outside-in perspective — using only what an automated tool can observe by making HTTP requests and analyzing responses, without access to source code, server configuration, or infrastructure.

My system analyzes CSP headers, other security headers (Strict-Transport-Security, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy), SRI on external script and style resources, and mixed content. From this observable surface, what can be reliably inferred about the security posture, and what are the fundamental limits?

Consider the CSP analysis problem: a CSP header can be parsed and analyzed for dangerous patterns (unsafe-inline, unsafe-eval, wildcard sources, data: URIs in script-src). But whether a CSP is effective depends on the actual content of the page — a CSP that allows 'nonce-{value}' is only as secure as the nonce implementation server-side. The header analysis cannot verify nonce uniqueness, nonce entropy, or whether nonces are correctly applied to all inline scripts. What can be stated with confidence from header analysis alone?

The deeper problem: a site may have a strong CSP header but be vulnerable to DOM-based XSS that doesn't involve injected script elements at all — prototype pollution, innerHTML assignments with user-controlled data in trusted scripts, postMessage handlers without origin validation. These vulnerabilities are invisible to header analysis and require dynamic testing or source code review. How should a header-analysis-based security scanner communicate its scope of analysis so users understand that passing the header checks does not mean the site is secure?

Reason through the concept of "observable security signals" versus "actual security posture" and propose how an automated external security analyzer should frame its findings to be maximally useful without creating false confidence. What disclosure language and scope limitations should accompany security scores produced by automated header analysis tools?
